training_organizations.name: Georgia DFCS – Office of Training and Professional Development
training_organizations.description: The Georgia Division of Family & Children Services operates an Office of Training that educates new child welfare case managers and provides ongoing development for staff. The training covers Georgia’s intake and investigative policies, foster care and permanency procedures, and specialized skills like interviewing children and assessing safety.

training_organizations.name: Georgia Child Welfare Training Collaborative (GSU)
training_organizations.description: A partnership between Georgia State University and DFCS that extends child welfare training to community partners and caregivers. This collaborative offers courses and workshops to foster parents, law enforcement, educators, and other community stakeholders to better coordinate with DFCS and improve outcomes for children.

training_organizations.name: Georgia CASA (Court Appointed Special Advocates)
training_organizations.description: A statewide nonprofit network that recruits and trains volunteers to advocate for abused and neglected children in Georgia’s juvenile courts. CASA volunteers are appointed by judges to represent the child’s best interests; the state CASA organization supports local CASA programs to ensure volunteers are properly trained and supported in their role.

policies.TribalFoster: No, Tribes within state do not provide foster care
policies.ScreenerQual_SW: Yes, recommended or preferred, but not required
policies.FatalitiesReview: Yes, reviews are required for all or some cases
policies.Def_Subtype_Abuse: Emotional Abuse includes domestic violence exposure; Physical Abuse includes factitious disorder by proxy; Sexual Abuse includes sex trafficking (sexual servitude) and sexual exploitation
policies.Def_Subtype_Neglect: Neglect includes abandonment, inadequate supervision (inadequate care and protection), inadequate food, clothing, shelter, inadequate health care (medical, dental, mental), educational/cognitive neglect, and suffocation/drowning
policies.NearFatalitiesReview: Yes, reviews are required for all or some cases
policies.ConsentDecree_Specify: Kenny A. vs. Sonny Perdue Consent Decree, which has been modified to Modified Consent Decree and Exit Plan
policies.Reporter_OtherSpecify: Child service organization personnel; Persons that are employees or volunteers at a hospital, school, social agency or similar facility
policies.InvestReq_OtherSpecify: Meet the emergency needs of the family; Link family to community resources; Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act signature; Jointly investigate with law enforcement, as applicable
policies.ScreenReq_OtherSpecify: Completion of the Family Functioning Assessment
policies.ReportInfo_OtherSpecify: The likelihood of reoccurrence; Current safety of the child
policies.DefAge_VaryByTypeSpecify: Sexual abuse of child includes consensual sex acts when sex acts are between minors involving an individual under 14, however, this does not include consensual sex acts between a minor and adult who is not more than 4 years older than the minor
policies.DefPerp_VaryByTypeSpecify: Sexual exploitation and labor trafficking do not require the perpetrator to be a parent, guardian or legal custodian.
policies.InvestQual_TrainingSpecify: The CPS Training involves Fundamentals, CPS Specific Training, Simulations and post training; Supervisors must complete Mandated Supervisor Training.
policies.AltResp_Inelig_OtherSpecify: Prenatal abuse; Trafficking a child for labor servitude (labor trafficking)
policies.ReporterPenalty_OtherSpecify: Child service organization personnel; Persons that are employees or volunteers at a hospital, school, social agency or similar facility
policies.ScreenerQual_TrainingSpecify: Standardized Training (2-4 weeks) consists of Child Protective Service Intake policy and procedures, Impending and Present Danger, Decision Making and observation. Upon training completion, Centralized Intake Specialists receives hands-on field training including navigating CICC Specialized technology. Coaching and professional development are continued through annual and ongoing training.
policies.InvestReq_MHEvalCases_Specify: May be reviewed for mothers of infants left in a safe place.
policies.ScreenRiskAssess_OtherSpecify: Review the information reported in each area of Family Functioning to determine if there is any indication of present or impending danger around family functioning.
policies.InvestReq_MedEvalCases_Specify: Substance-exposed infants; Physical abuse; Abandoned infants; Whenever there is a question of whether or not a child needs to be examined by a medical professional, the caregiver is asked to seek a medical consultation
policies.ScreenerQual_ExperienceSpecify: Preferred 3 years of experience in a customer service setting communication information or 2 years of experience at the lower level Customer Service Rep 2 or position equivalent
policies.AltResp_EligibilityMaltreatment: Only certain types of maltreatment are eligible
policies.CaseManagerQual_TrainingSpecify: The Foster Care Training involves Fundamentals, Foster Care Specific Training, Simulations and post training; Supervisors must go through Mandated Supervisor Training
policies.AltResp_ServiceReferralOtherSpec: When there is a determination of need and the assessment identifies the need for formal and/or informal services, Division of Family & Children Services shall continue the partnership with families in order to engage them to participate in identified services
